---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CompressPdfConverter from '~/components/CompressPdfConverter';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Compress PDF · a → b"
  description="Shrink PDF file size in your browser. Text stays selectable. Files never leave your device."
>
  <header class="mb-8">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">Compress PDF</h1>
    <p class="mt-2 text-lg" style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      Shrink PDF file size — entirely in your browser. Text stays selectable.
    </p>
  </header>

  <CompressPdfConverter client:load />

  <aside
    class="mt-12 rounded-xl border p-6"
    style="border-color: var(--color-border); background: var(--color-accent-soft)"
  >
    <h2
      class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wider uppercase"
      style="color: var(--color-accent)"
    >
      How this works
    </h2>
    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>Light</strong> and <strong>Balanced</strong> use image recompression: embedded
      images are downsized to match how big they actually appear on the page, re-encoded with
      mozjpeg, then a qpdf-wasm pass repacks the PDF's structure. Text, fonts, vectors, form
      fields, and bookmarks are all preserved.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>Strong</strong> uses a different technique for much bigger savings (often 80–90%):
      each page is rendered to a JPEG and rebuilt with an invisible text layer overlaid at the
      original character positions. <strong>Text stays selectable and searchable</strong>, but
      form widgets, signature fields, bookmarks, annotations, and accessibility tags are not
      preserved. Use Light or Balanced if you need to keep those.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed">
      If we'd produce a bigger file, we hand back your original unchanged. Either way, your
      file never leaves your device.
    </p>
  </aside>
</BaseLayout>
